The parallelism between Jewish and Batavian sentiment is not acci- dental ; both nations revolted because they thought they saw providential signs (iv. 54 3) of the dissolution of the empire; when it appeared that the cohesion of the empire was proof against the dis- tractions of a war of succession,

both recognised the empire, with a quasi-religious awe, as practically indissoluble. True, the speech as- signed to Agrippa is placed before the death of Nero ; but it probably represents rather Josephus’ own sentiments at the time of writing than the king's at the time of speak- ing3 and the historian⁷s political conduct is best accounted for by supposing the course of his opinions to be the same as the Batavians'. Cf. Jos. B. J. vii. 4. 2.
